Exercise 14.50: Show the possible class-type conversion sequences for the
initializations of ex1 and ex2. Explain whether the initializations are legal or
not.

struct LongDouble {
    LongDouble(double = 0.0);
    operator double();
    operator float();
};
LongDouble ldObj;
int ex1 = ldObj;
float ex2 = ldObj;

Answer:
ex1 --> int ex1 = (int)ldObj --> Path A: int ex1 = (int)(double)ldObj, Path B: int ex1 = (int)(float)ldObj (Two candidates) --> Thus call is ambiguous
and the initialization is not legal.
ex2 --> float ex2 = (float)ldObj --> Path A: float ex2 = (float)ldObj (exact match), Path B:float ex2 = (float)(double)ldObj
--> Since Path A is an exact match the initialization will be legal.

Exercise 14.51: Show the conversion sequences (if any) needed to call each
version of calc and explain why the best viable function is selected.

void calc(int);
void calc(LongDouble);
double dval;
calc(dval); // which calc?

Answer:
Option 1: double --> int, promotion
Option 2: double --> LongDouble, class-type conversion

The order of choice is :
1.exact match
2.const conversion
3.promotion
4.arithmetic or pointer conversion
5.class-type conversion

Since option 1 is by integer promotion and is ranked 3 and option 2 is class-type conversion than option 1 is more viable
and is selected.

Exercise 14.52: Which operator+, if any, is selected for each of the
addition expressions? List the candidate functions, the viable functions, and
the type conversions on the arguments for each viable function:

struct LongDouble {
    LongDouble(double = 0.0);
    operator double();
    operator float();
    // member operator+ for illustration purposes; + is usually a nonmember
    LongDouble operator+(const SmallInt&);
    // other members as in § 14.9.2 (p. 587)
};
LongDouble operator+(LongDouble&, double);
SmallInt si;
LongDouble ld;
1)ld = si + ld;
2)ld = ld + si;

Answer:
1)
Candidate functions:
LongDouble operator+(const SmallInt&);
LongDouble operator+(LongDouble&, double);
Viable functions:
LongDouble operator+(const SmallInt&);
LongDouble operator+(LongDouble&, double);
Type conversions: Option A: LongDouble -> double/float -> int --> SmallInt --> ambiguous ,Option B: SmallInt -> int --> double -> LongDouble OR LongDouble -> double --> ambiguous
2)
Candidate functions:
LongDouble operator+(LongDouble&, double);
LongDouble operator+(const SmallInt&);
Viable functions:
LongDouble operator+(LongDouble&, double);
LongDouble operator+(const SmallInt&);
Type conversions:
LongDouble --> double --> int --> SmallInt
No conversion is needed for the second option and thus it will be chosen.

Exercise 14.53: Given the definition of SmallInt on page 588, determine
whether the following addition expression is legal. If so, what addition
operator is used? If not, how might you change the code to make it legal?

SmallInt s1;
double d = s1 + 3.14;

Answer:
Ambiguous since s1 can be converted to int and then double OR 3.14 can be converted to int and then SmallInt.
fix:
double d = s1 + SmallInt(3.14);